#Text=2. Building Overview , Current HVAC system
#Text=The building under study is mostly office spaces .
#Text=Building construction was completed in 1976 .
#Text=The current HVAC system was commissioned that same year .
#Text=The building has six floors with a basement .
#Text=Windows are very limited with only two small windows per floor and at the front entrance .
#Text=The area distribution of the seven floors is given in Table 1 .
#Text=The current HVAC system is a DFDD with electric heating and has multiple maintenance issues .
#Text=A DFDD has two supply ducts running to each conditioned space .
#Text=One duct supplies cold air and the other supplies warm air .
#Text=Air from both ducts is blended in a mixing box to provide air at a desired temperature to the conditioned space .
#Text=A generic diagram of a DFDD system is shown in
#Text=Figure 1
#Text=.
#Text=The building has thermostats , which are not programmable .
#Text=The orientation of the building entrance is south .
#Text=The building has an addition on the east side , which has a new HVAC system .
#Text=For modeling purposes , however , only the original building with DFDD is considered .
#Text=The zones of the old building and the addition are separate .
#Text=Dual-duct systems , in general , require more ductwork and dampers , and therefore occupy more space .
#Text=One of the most problematic issues with dual-duct systems is that a volume of air much larger than that required by the building , must be cooled , heated , and circulated .
#Text=DFDD systems tend to be noisier since the noise and vibration associated with the air passing over the mixing dampers are directly above the conditioned space .
#Text=In addition , the dampers in dual-duct mixing boxes frequently leak , even when they are supposed to be fully closed .
#Text=During cooling operation , the leakage of the warm duct increases the required energy for conditioning the space .
#Text=The leakage is a function of construction quality and of the duct static pressure .
#Text=Leakage ratios vary between roughly 3 percent and 20 percent , which is higher than single-duct systems .
#Text=Because health professionals are present around the clock , the building is set to be always occupied in all design considerations .

#Text=To have a comparative study of this building with similar buildings across the US , the electric energy utilization index ( EUI ) for the building was calculated using ENERGY STAR Portfolio Manager .
#Text=The ENERGY STAR score of the building was found to be 39 .
#Text=The site electric EUI was found to be 133.4 kBtu/ft2 , while the US average with similar office occupancy and conditions is 44.4 kBtu/ft2 .
#Text=Thus , the energy consumption of the building was very high , indicating a need to lower the energy consumption .
#Text=Table 2 shows the average local area utility prices used for analysis .
